<div class="article-advert-body">
<div id="js-article-text" class="article-text float-l " >
<h1>Row over BBC presenter's Darling defence</h1>
<p>By <a href="/home/search.html?s=y&authornamef=Daily+Mail+Reporter" class="author" rel="nofollow">Daily Mail Reporter</a> and <a href="/home/search.html?s=y&authornamef=Paul+Revoir" class="author" rel="nofollow">Paul Revoir</a><br/>
<span class="article-timestamp">
<strong>UPDATED:</strong>

02:56 EST, 4 September 2008

</span>
</p>
<div id="articleIconLinksContainer">
<ul>
<li class="share-facebook" onclick='postToFB(); return false;'></li>
<li class="share-twitter" onclick='postToTWTTR(); return false;'>
</li>
<li class="share-gplus"><span class="g-interactivepost"
data-contenturl="http://www.dailymail.co.uk/money/news/article-1641264/Row-over-BBC-presenters-Darling-defence.html"
data-contentdeeplinkid="/pages"
data-clientid="746589970956-e10ciaf67a1id9ggu75ph3ds0sthn7j6.apps.googleusercontent.com"
data-cookiepolicy="single_host_origin"
data-prefilltext="Row over BBC presenter's Darling defence"
data-calltoactionlabel="VIEW"
data-calltoactionurl="http://www.dailymail.co.uk/money/news/article-1641264/Row-over-BBC-presenters-Darling-defence.html">
<a onclick='postToGPlus(); return false;'></a>
</span></li>
<li class="share-icons" id="shareLinkTop"><a
class="js-sl share-link" href="#socialLinks"> </a> <script
type="text/javascript">
var twitterVia = 'DailyMailUS';
DM.has('shareLinkTop', 'shareLinks', {
'id': '1641264',
'title': 'Row over BBC presenter\'s Darling defence',
'url': 'http://www.dailymail.co.uk/money/news/article-1641264/Row-over-BBC-presenters-Darling-defence.html',
'eTwitterStatus': 'Row%20over%20BBC%20journalist\'s%20Darling%20defence%20http:\/\/www.dailymail.co.uk\/money\/news\/article-1641264\/Row-over-BBC-presenters-Darling-defence.html%20via%20@' + twitterVia,
'articleChannelFollowButton': 'thisismoney ',
'isChannel': false 
});
</script></li>
</ul>
<a class="comments-count home" href="#comments"> <span></span>
<p class="count-number">
0
</p>
<p class="count-text">
View <br /> comments
</p>
</a>
</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="clear"> </div>
<p>Alistair Darling was right to give a grim assessment of the economy, according to an extraordinary public defence from Radio 4 Today programme presenter Evan Davis. 
</p>
<div class="floatTimRHS"><img src="http://img.thisismoney.co.uk/i/pix/2008/09/EvanDavis_203x150.jpg" alt="Evan Davis" border="1" width="203" height="150"><p class="imageCaption"><strong>Evan Davis: </strong>The Chancellor was just telling the truth, he said</p></div>
<p>He argued that the Chancellor should not be vilified because he was just telling the truth. 
</p>
<p>But Davis, perhaps better known as frontman on the BBC TV programme Dragons' Den, was immediately criticised by Tories. 
</p>
<p>They said it was not the role of a BBC presenter to defend the Government's public statements or to take sides in the row. 
</p>
<p>Some MPs claimed Davis's comments, on his Today programme blog, could compromise the presenter the next time he is questioning politicians. 
</p>
<p>Mr Darling's remark last weekend that the economic situation was 'arguably the worst in 60 years' was followed by the pound crashing to a record low. Conservative leader David Cameron accused the Chancellor of 'talking down' the economy. 
</p>
<p>But on his blog Davis, 46, a former economics editor at the BBC, offered his personal view that Mr Darling 'deserves defending' from the 'various accusations laid at his door' over talking us into recession and causing the pound to plunge. 
</p>
<p>He denied the Chancellor had 'dropped a clanger' and said talk of him failing to reassure consumers and investors was wrong. 
</p>
<p>Davis said: 'In the face of all the evidence to the contrary, I think it would have been a mistake for Mr Darling to have stuck to his previous line that we are uniquely well-placed to weather the storm. 
</p>
<p>'It seems unlikely he had special powers to move us all with his words of encouragement and positive thinking - if only he hadn't blown it. 
</p>
<p>'If political spin could move the economy so far, let's improve the quality of our schools by demanding that education ministers tell us inner city schools are better than suburban ones. And maybe the Foreign Secretary could get Russia out of Georgia by telling us they are not there at all. 
</p>
<p>'No, if we could make the economy strong by lying about it, I would be out there for lying all the time. But it didn't work in the Soviet Union, and it won't work in a country with a free press either. Better that Mr Darling tells us what he thinks, than he tells us what we'd like to hear.' 
</p>
<p>Critics feel Davis stepped over the line. Conservative MP David Davies said: 'It is completely wrong for a BBC presenter to start defending Government actions when they have made mistakes.' He added: 'Why is a Labour Chancellor being helped out by a presenter of the BBC's flagship political programme?' 
</p>
<p>A BBC spokesman said: 'Evan Davis clearly states at the start of his blog - and couldn't be clearer - that he is not writing to support or oppose the Chancellor. It's purely an argument about the media and how it reports.' 
</p>
<p>But Mr Davies said the blog risked raising further fears of a Left-wing bias at the BBC. Jim Naughtie, another Today presenter, caused a row in 2005 when he asked Labour's Ed Balls: 'If we win the election, does Gordon Brown want to remain Chancellor?' 
</p>
<div class="column-content cleared narrow">
